  "summary": "Betty Gregg expresses her frustrations to Mr. Parker Pyne, complaining that Basil Chester tends to prioritize his mother's influence and is dull due to being pampered. Pyne conducts a brief compatibility test with Betty regarding her habits and preferences, concluding that she and Basil are well-suited. During this time, Pyne advises Mrs. Chester to act reluctantly regarding her son's engagement to maintain her leverage.\n\nAfter a week-long vacation in Soleil, Pyne returns to the Pinewood Hotel to find Mrs. Chester and a tearful, pale Miss Betsey drinking tea. Their meeting is interrupted by Basil, who arrives from the beach with a glamorous, dark-skinned woman named Delores (also referred to as Miss Ramona or Miss Lamorna). Dressed in light blue chiffon and heavy makeup, Delores dismisses the other women and calls Basil \"darling\" before leading him away to her hotel.\n\nFollowing their departure, Betty leaves in anger, and Mrs. Chester expresses regret over her son's behavior. Pyne attempts to reassure Mrs. Chester, suggesting that Delores's presence may have broken Basil's infatuation with Betty. When Basil returns, he defends his right to have friends and dismisses his mother's concerns regarding Betty's jealousy. A few days later, Basil breaks his scheduled plans for a picnic with Betty to go to Fontainebleau with Delores and her friends.",
